<p>
  <strong>A monthsary is the monthly anniversary of the day your relationship began.</strong> If you got together on the 14th, then the 14th of every month is a monthsary — a small milestone marking one more month together. Couples celebrate them the way they'd celebrate a yearly anniversary, just smaller and more often.
</p>

<p>
  The word is especially popular in the <strong>Philippines</strong> and across Southeast Asia, where marking each month of a relationship is a widely loved tradition — but it's used by couples everywhere, particularly during the first year when every single month still feels like a big deal.
</p>

<h2>What Does "Monthsary" Mean?</h2>

<p>
  "Monthsary" is a blend of <em>month</em> + <em>anniversary</em>. It simply means "monthly anniversary." You'll also see it spelled <em>monthsarry</em> or <em>monthsery</em> — all the same thing, just informal spellings of a word that grew out of everyday couple-speak rather than a dictionary.
</p>

<h2>Is It "Monthsary" or "Mensiversary"?</h2>

<p>
  Both exist, and both mean the same thing. <strong>Monthsary</strong> is the everyday word couples actually use. <strong>Mensiversary</strong> is the technically correct one: "anniversary" comes from the Latin <em>annus</em> (year), so the monthly version swaps in <em>mensis</em> (month). Nobody will correct you for saying monthsary — and almost nobody says mensiversary out loud.
</p>

<h2>How Does a Monthsary Work?</h2>

<p>
  A monthsary follows the <strong>calendar day</strong>, not a fixed number of days. Your monthsary is the same day-of-month as your start date, every month:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Started dating <strong>March 8</strong> → monthsaries on April 8, May 8, June 8…</li>
  <li>April 8 is your <strong>1st monthsary</strong>, May 8 your <strong>2nd</strong>, and so on.</li>
  <li>Twelve monthsaries make one year — your first <strong>anniversary</strong>.</li>
</ul>

<p>
  Because months aren't all the same length, the gap between two monthsaries is 28 to 31 days — not a flat 30. For the full counting rules (including the classic edge case: what happens if you got together on the 31st), see our guide on <a href="/blog/how-to-count-months-in-a-relationship">how to count months in a relationship</a>.
</p>

<h2>Monthsary vs Anniversary: What's the Difference?</h2>

<p>
  <strong>A monthsary is celebrated every month; an anniversary is celebrated every year.</strong> Both are counted from the same start date — the day your relationship began.
</p>

