<h2>Is a Monthsary Celebrated Every Month?</h2>

<p>
  It can be, but it doesn't have to be. Most couples celebrate every month during their <strong>first year</strong>, when each one still feels like an achievement. After the first anniversary, many keep only the meaningful ones — the 18th, the 24th — and shift to yearly anniversaries. Plenty of couples keep counting monthsaries for years. There's no rule; celebrate the ones that mean something to you both.
</p>

<h2>Which Monthsaries Do Couples Actually Celebrate?</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>1st monthsary</strong> — the very first month together, usually the sweetest one.</li>
  <li><strong>3rd monthsary</strong> — the early "we're really doing this" mark.</li>
  <li><strong>6th monthsary</strong> — half a year; a big one for most couples.</li>
  <li><strong>12th monthsary</strong> — one full year, and your first real anniversary.</li>
  <li><strong>18th &amp; 24th</strong> — a year and a half, then two years together.</li>
</ul>

<p>
  Some couples also track day-based milestones alongside monthsaries — 100 days, 500 days, 1000 days. If that's you, our <a href="/blog/how-long-have-we-been-dating">guide to relationship milestones worth celebrating</a> covers what each one means and how to mark it.
</p>

<h2>How Do You Know Your Monthsary Date?</h2>

<p>
  Take the day-of-month you started dating — that's your monthsary date, forever. Got together on the 6th? Every 6th is a monthsary. You never recalculate it; it's locked to that calendar day.
</p>

<p>
  If you'd rather not count in your head, our free <a href="/tools/monthsary-counter">monthsary counter</a> does it instantly: enter your start date and it shows which monthsary is next, its exact date, and a live countdown in days. For totals in days, weeks and years — plus 100-day and 1000-day milestones — use the <a href="/tools/anniversary-calculator">anniversary calculator</a> instead.
</p>

<h2>Quick Recap</h2>

<ul>
  <li>A monthsary is the <strong>monthly anniversary</strong> of the day you got together.</li>
  <li>It falls on the <strong>same day-of-month</strong> as your start date.</li>
  <li>Monthsary = every month. Anniversary = every year. Same start date.</li>
  <li>12 monthsaries = 1 anniversary.</li>
  <li>Celebrate the ones that matter to you — there's no rule.</li>
</ul>

